SIMPLE: condone
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Condone
<hw>Con*done"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Condoned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Condoning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>condonare</ets>, <ets>-donatum</ets>, to give up, remit, forgive;
<ets>con-</ets> + <ets>donare</ets> to give. See <er>Donate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To pardon; to forgive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fraud which he had either concocted or <qex>condoned</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It would have been magnanimous in the men then in power to have
overlooked all these things, and, <qex>condoning</qex> the politics, to
have rewarded the poetry of Burns.</q> <rj><qau>J. C.
Shairp.</qau></rj></p>

<p><-- 1b. to consider or treat as if harmless or trivial -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To pardon; to overlook the offense
of; esp., to forgive for a violation of the marriage law; -- said of
either the husband or the wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Condor</ent>⟦br⟧
